pullRequest.body:
Moves:
- `*coeSubmodule*`, `*coe_toSubmodule*`, `*to_submodule*`, `*coe_submodule*`, `*coe_to_submodule*` -> `*toSubmodule*`
- `*coe_linearMap*` -> `*toLinearMap*`
- `*to_lieHom*` -> `*toLieHom*`
- `*coe_linearEquiv*`, `*to_linearEquiv*` -> `*toLinearEquiv*`
- `*coe_lieSubalgebra*`, `*to_lieSubalgebra*` -> `*toLieSubalgebra*`

special cases:
* `LieIdeal.coe_toSubalgebra` -> `LieIdeal.coe_toLieSubalgebra`
* `LieSubalgebra.coe_to_submodule` -> `LieSubalgebra.coe_toSubmodule`
* `LieSubmodule.coe_toSubmodule` and similar: unchanged
* `sInf_coe_toSubmodule'` -> `sInf_toSubmodule_eq_iInf`
* `sSup_coe_toSubmodule'` -> `sSup_toSubmodule_eq_iSup`

PR follows [this Zulip discussion](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Algebra.2ELie.2ESubmodule.2C.20Algebra.2ELie.2ESubalgebra.20naming)

```suggestion
theorem coe_toSubmodule : ((L' : Submodule R L) : Set L) = L' :=
```
Looks like an over-eager replacement
This name still looks wrong. Can you clarify what the LHS and RHS are?

I believe it says: coercing a Lie ideal to a Lie subalgebra, then to a (vanilla) submodule, is the same as coercing the Lie ideal to a Lie submodule, then to a (vanilla) submodule. Only the last of these 4 mappings is written out explicitly, despite all 4 coercions being registered.
maybe `coe_toLieSubalgebra_eq_coe_toLieSubmodule`?
So concretely this is a commutative square. simp is better at commutative triangles... Is there not a direct coercion `LieIdeal R L` to `Submodule R L`?
To be clear, we don't have to block this PR on this issue. The new name is already a clear improvement on the previous one
I don't know. To be honest I feel like Algebra/Lie/* is overusing coercions in a weird way.
update: see #20408

While you're at it, the `_iff` is redundant here
```suggestion
theorem toSubmodule_eq_bot : (N : Submodule R M) = âŠ¥ â†” N = âŠ¥ := by
```
Same here

Uh oh, this lemma is backwards. Not your problem here, but I'd leave a comment to remember it
```suggestion
-- TODO(YaÃ«l): turn around
theorem disjoint_iff_toSubmodule :
    Disjoint N N' â†” Disjoint (N : Submodule R M) (N' : Submodule R M) := by
```
